<rfc version="3" ipr="trust200902" docName="draft-morgan-ten64-00" 
     submissionType="IETF" category="info" xml:lang="en">
  <front>
    <title abbrev="Ten10b">Text Encoded Base Ten Numbers Version 1 (Ten10b_v1)</title>
    
    <author initials="S." surname="Morgan" fullname="Scott Morgan">
      <organization>Adligo Inc.</organization>
      <address>
        <email>scott@adligo.com</email>
        <uri>https://github.com/adligo/ten10b_v1.adligo.org</uri>
      </address>
    </author>

    <date year="2026" month="April" day="1"/>

    <area>Applications and Real-Time</area>
    <workgroup>Internet Engineering Task Force</workgroup>
    
    <abstract>
      <t>
        Ten10b, is a 
        <xref target="positional-number-systems-wikipedia" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        positional number system</xref> designed to be encoded 
        in <xref target="utf-8-rfc-3629" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">UTF-8</xref> text.
        Ten10b is based on the system 
        you likely learned in elementary school and used throughout your mathematics 
        courses.  However, it is a <xref target="discrete-system-wikipedia" format="none" sectionFormat="bare"> 
        discrete system</xref> designed to provide the maximum clarity for the serialization of numbers 
        (which fit on a single line of text) across the internet. Although the 
        numbers encoded by the Ten10b system MAY represent a point on a continuous 
        curve (aka an <xref target="integral-wikipedia" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        integral</xref> or simply <xref target="analog-wikipedia" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        analog</xref>), the text itself is a <xref target="discrete-system-wikipedia" format="none" sectionFormat="bare"> 
        discrete system</xref>. In addition, it SHOULD be noted 
        that since all <xref target="binary-number-systems-wikipedia" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        binary number systems </xref>
        are discrete, by proxy, all number systems built on top of them are by proxy 
        <xref target="discrete-system-wikipedia"  format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        discrete number systems</xref>. This 
        includes <xref target="ieee-754-wikipedia" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        floating point numbers</xref> which MAY 
        introduce rounding and extra decimal place issues when printed or converted to other <xref target="positional-number-systems-wikipedia" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        positional number systems</xref>.
      </t>
      <t>
        Ten10b codifies five types of numbers which MAY be represented with 
        <xref target="utf-8-rfc-3629" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        UTF-8 text</xref> as follows: <xref target="integers" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">Integers</xref>, 
        <xref target="integer-fractions" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        Integer Fractions</xref>, <xref target="integer-loops" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        Integer Loops</xref>, <xref target="decimals" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        Decimals</xref>, and <xref target="decimal-loops" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        Decimal Loops (aka. Repeating Decimals) </xref>. 
        Ten10b allows for numbers to be of any size, any number of characters. 
        However, since Ten10b numbers MUST be parsable from a single line of text, 
        <xref target="line-wrapping-wikipedia" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        line wrapping</xref> SHOULD NOT be used 
        with Ten10b. To improve human-readability, we suggest using 
        <xref target="ten64" format="none" sectionFormat="bare">
        Ten64 </xref> for numbers that do NOT fit on a single line. Finally, 
        Ten10b users SHOULD use a 92-character number sequence character limiter.
      </t>
    </abstract>
  </front>
  
